{"type":"text","timestamp":1775876759858,"sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","part":{"id":"prt_d7a7ff6bc001Qw3ShmrINA9snc","messageID":"msg_d7a7fd09a00164Iv5jnKKgJxaQ","sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","type":"text","text":"I'll write a delta-spec.md file for the agentcube project focusing on AR-027 (SDK CodeInterpreterClient) using the GIVEN/WHEN/THEN format.","time":{"start":1775876759854,"end":1775876759854}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775876759896,"sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","part":{"id":"prt_d7a80e132001raX2Jm2NSSR2wz","messageID":"msg_d7a7fd09a00164Iv5jnKKgJxaQ","sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-5f2ef82e12364c2298efb9a3468287a2","state":{"status":"error","input":{"content":"# Delta Specification: AR-027 — SDK CodeInterpreterClient\n\n## AR Metadata\n- **AR ID**: AR-027\n- **Title**: SDK CodeInterpreterClient\n- **Module**: sdk-python\n- **Language**: Python\n- **Size**: M\n- **Status**: Implementation Required\n\n## Purpose\nThis delta specification defines implementation requirements for the `CodeInterpreterClient` class in the AgentCube Python SDK, focusing on session lifecycle management, code execution, file operations, and HTTP client interactions.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: CodeInterpreterClient initialization with environment variable resolution\nThe system SHALL resolve `workload_manager_url` from parameter or `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` environment variable, resolve `router_url` from parameter or `ROUTER_URL` environment variable (required), and resolve `auth_token` from parameter or `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token`.\n\n#### Scenario: All parameters provided explicitly\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(name=\"test\", namespace=\"dev\", ttl=1800, workload_manager_url=\"http://wm:8080\", router_url=\"http://router:9000\", auth_token=\"custom-token\")` is called\n- **WHEN** initialization completes\n- **THEN** the client SHALL use the provided `workload_manager_url`, `router_url`, and `auth_token` values directly\n\n#### Scenario: Workload Manager URL from environment\n- **GIVEN** environment variable `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` is set to `http://wm-default:8080`\n- **WHEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(router_url=\"http://router:9000\")` is called without `workload_manager_url`\n- **THEN** the client SHALL resolve `workload_manager_url` to `http://wm-default:8080`\n\n#### Scenario: Router URL missing required parameter\n- **GIVEN** neither `router_url` parameter nor `ROUTER_URL` environment variable is set\n- **WHEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is initialized\n- **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError` with message containing \"Router URL must be provided\"\n\n#### Scenario: Auth token from Kubernetes service account\n- **GIVEN** `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token` contains valid JWT token\n- **WHEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is called without `auth_token` parameter\n- **THEN** the client SHALL read and use the token from the file path via `read_token_from_file`\n\n#### Scenario: Service account token file missing\n- **GIVEN** `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token` does not exist\n- **WHEN** `auth_token` is not provided and `read_token_from_file` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL return empty string and `auth_token` SHALL be set to `None` (no Authorization header will be set)\n\n### Requirement: Session lifecycle with context manager support\nThe system SHALL support context manager protocol via `__enter__` and `__exit__`, create session via control plane if `session_id` not provided, and cleanup resources on exit.\n\n#### Scenario: Context manager entry with existing session_id\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(session_id=\"existing-session\")` is created\n- **WHEN** the client enters a context manager block via `with client:`\n- **THEN** `__enter__` SHALL return `self` without creating a new session\n\n#### Scenario: Context manager entry creates new session\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is created without `session_id`\n- **WHEN** the client enters a context manager block\n- **THEN** the system SHALL call `ControlPlaneClient.create_session()`, set `session_id` to returned value, initialize `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient`, and return `self`\n\n#### Scenario: Context manager normal exit\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` is used in a `with` block and `session_id` was created during entry\n- **WHEN** the block exits normally\n- **THEN** `__exit__` SHALL call `stop()`, which closes data-plane client, deletes control-plane session via `ControlPlaneClient.delete_session()`, and closes control-plane HTTP session\n\n#### Scenario: Context manager exit with exception\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` is used in a `with` block and an exception occurs in the block\n- **WHEN** the block exits with exception\n- **THEN** `__exit__` SHALL call `stop()` to clean up resources, then re-raise the exception with exception info passed to `__exit__`\n\n#### Scenario: Manual stop after context manager\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` has already exited its context manager and `stop()` was called\n- **WHEN** `stop()` is called again manually\n- **THEN** subsequent calls SHALL be idempotent and not raise errors\n\n### Requirement: Data plane initialization failure handling\nThe system SHALL handle data plane initialization failures by cleaning up created sessions before re-raising.\n\n#### Scenario: Data plane init fails after session creation\n- **GIVEN** `session_id` was not provided and `ControlPlaneClient.create_session()` succeeded returning \"new-session-123\"\n- **WHEN** `_init_data_plane()` raises an exception during initialization\n- **THEN** the client SHALL log a warning message, call `ControlPlaneClient.delete_session(\"new-session-123\")`, set `session_id` to `None`, and re-raise the original exception\n\n#### Scenario: Data plane init fails with existing session\n- **GIVEN** `session_id=\"existing-456\"` was provided to constructor\n- **WHEN** `_init_data_plane()` raises an exception\n- **THEN** the client SHALL NOT attempt to delete the session (as it was not created by this client), but SHALL re-raise the exception\n\n### Requirement: Command execution with timeout and error handling\nThe system SHALL execute shell commands via data plane, parse JSON response, handle non-zero exit codes, and support custom timeouts.\n\n#### Scenario: Successful command execution\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient` is initialized and session is active\n- **WHEN** `execute_command(\"echo 'hello world'\")` is called with default timeout\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST to `api/execute` with JSON `{\"command\": [\"echo\", \"hello world\"], \"timeout\": \"120s\"}`, wait for response, and return `stdout` from response JSON\n\n#### Scenario: Command with non-zero exit code\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command(\"ls /nonexistent\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the response JSON contains `exit_code: 1` and `stderr: \"No such file or directory\"`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL raise `CommandExecutionError(exit_code=1, stderr=\"No such file or directory\", command=\"ls /nonexistent\")`\n\n#### Scenario: Custom timeout for command execution\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command(\"sleep 10\", timeout=30.0)` is called\n- **WHEN** the request is prepared\n- **THEN** the body SHALL include `timeout: \"30s\"` and the HTTP read timeout SHALL be `32.0` seconds (30 + 2.0 buffer)\n\n#### Scenario: Command timeout without custom override\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command(\"long-running-command\")` is called without timeout parameter\n- **WHEN** the default timeout is applied\n- **THEN** the body SHALL include `timeout: \"120s\"` (from `self.timeout`) and read timeout SHALL be `122.0` seconds\n\n#### Scenario: Command with list argument format\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command([\"ls\", \"-la\", \"/tmp\"])` is called with list of strings\n- **WHEN** the command is executed\n- **THEN** the data plane SHALL receive the list directly in the JSON body `{\"command\": [\"ls\", \"-la\", \"/tmp\"], \"timeout\": \"120s\"}`\n\n### Requirement: Code execution with language-specific handling\nThe system SHALL support `run_code()` for multiple languages with special handling for Python via file write and execute.\n\n#### Scenario: Python code execution\n- **GIVEN** `run_code(language=\"python\", code=\"print('hello')\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the method executes\n- **THEN** the system SHALL generate timestamped filename (e.g., `code_20250411_123456.py`), call `write_file(content=\"print('hello')\", remote_path=\"<filename>\")`, then call `execute_command(f\"python3 {filename}\")` and return result\n\n#### Scenario: Python code with alternative language identifier\n- **GIVEN** `run_code(language=\"py\", code=\"x = 1 + 2; print(x)\")` is called\n- **WHEN** language is detected as Python variant\n- **THEN** the system SHALL use the same file-write-and-execute pattern as `\"python\"` or `\"python3\"`\n\n#### Scenario: Non-Python code execution\n- **GIVEN** `run_code(language=\"bash\", code=\"echo 'hello from bash'\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the language is not a Python variant\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST directly to data plane `run_code` endpoint with `{\"language\": \"bash\", \"code\": \"echo 'hello from bash'\"}` body\n\n### Requirement: File operations via data plane\nThe system SHALL support write, upload, download, and list file operations with proper encoding and headers.\n\n#### Scenario: Write file with base64 encoding\n- **GIVEN** `write_file(content=\"hello world\", remote_path=\"/tmp/test.txt\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the request is sent\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST to `api/files` with JSON `{\"content\": \"<base64>\", \"path\": \"/tmp/test.txt\", \"mode\": \"0644\"}` where content is base64-encoded\n\n#### Scenario: Upload file via multipart\n- **GIVEN** `upload_file(local_path=\"/local/file.txt\", remote_path=\"/remote/file.txt\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the multipart request is sent\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST to `api/files` with `files={'file': open('/local/file.txt', 'rb')}`, `data={'path': '/remote/file.txt', 'mode': '0644'}`, and header `x-agentcube-session-id: <session_id>`\n\n#### Scenario: Download file with streaming\n- **GIVEN** `download_file(remote_path=\"/data/result.json\", local_path=\"./result.json\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the file is downloaded\n- **THEN** the system SHALL GET `api/files/data/result.json` (cleaned path) with `stream=True`, write response content to `./result.json`, and close response after writing\n\n#### Scenario: List files in directory\n- **GIVEN** `list_files(path=\"/home/user\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the request completes\n- **THEN** the system SHALL GET `api/files?path=/home/user` and return the JSON response (typically file listing)\n\n#### Scenario: List files default path\n- **GIVEN** `list_files()` is called without path argument\n- **WHEN** the request is sent\n- **THEN** the system SHALL use default path `.` and query `api/files?path=.`\n\n### Requirement: HTTP session management and connection pooling\nThe system SHALL use `requests.Session` with `HTTPAdapter` for connection pooling on control plane and data plane clients.\n\n#### Scenario: Create session with default pool settings\n- **GIVEN** `create_session()` is called without arguments\n- **WHEN** the session is created\n- **THEN** the system SHALL create `requests.Session`, mount `HTTPAdapter` with `pool_connections=10` and `pool_maxsize=10` for both `http://` and `https://`, and return the session\n\n#### Scenario: Control plane client with custom pool settings\n- **GIVEN** `ControlPlaneClient(pool_connections=20, pool_maxsize=20)` is initialized\n- **WHEN** the HTTP session is created\n- **THEN** the system SHALL use the custom pool values when calling `create_session()`\n\n#### Scenario: Data plane client uses provided session\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient` is constructed with all required parameters\n- **WHEN** initialization completes\n- **THEN** the client SHALL create its own HTTP session via `create_session()` with configured pool settings\n\n#### Scenario: Closing sessions\n- **GIVEN** a client has an active `requests.Session`\n- **WHEN** `close()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL call `self.session.close()` to properly close the session and release connections\n\n### Requirement: Logger configuration\nThe system SHALL configure logging with `get_logger()` utility supporting name and level parameters.\n\n#### Scenario: Logger with default INFO level\n- **GIVEN** `get_logger(\"agentcube.code_interpreter\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the logger is created\n- **THEN** the system SHALL return a `logging.Logger` instance with name `\"agentcube.code_interpreter\"` and level `logging.INFO`\n\n#### Scenario: Logger with custom level\n- **GIVEN** `get_logger(\"agentcube.client\", level=logging.DEBUG)` is called\n- **WHEN** the logger is created\n- **THEN** the system SHALL return a logger with level set to `logging.DEBUG`\n\n#### Scenario: Client initialization sets logger\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(verbose=True)` is initialized\n- **WHEN** the logger is set\n- **THEN** the client SHALL create logger with level based on `verbose` flag (DEBUG if True, INFO if False)\n\n### Requirement: Session header injection for data plane requests\nThe system SHALL inject `x-agentcube-session-id` header into all data plane requests.\n\n#### Scenario: Request includes session header\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient(session_id=\"session-abc\")` is initialized\n- **WHEN** any `_request()` method call is made\n- **THEN** the request headers SHALL include `x-agentcube-session-id: session-abc`\n\n#### Scenario: Multipart upload includes session header\n- **GIVEN** `upload_file()` is called\n- **WHEN** the multipart POST is prepared\n- **THEN** the request SHALL explicitly set `x-agentcube-session-id` header alongside the multipart files and data\n\n#### Scenario: JSON request includes session header\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command()` is called with a JSON body\n- **WHEN** the POST request is sent\n- **THEN** the request SHALL include both `Content-Type: application/json` and `x-agentcube-session-id: <session_id>` headers\n\n### Requirement: Base URL construction for data plane\nThe system SHALL construct data plane base URL from router URL, namespace, and CR name unless explicitly provided.\n\n#### Scenario: Base URL from router and metadata\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient(router_url=\"http://router:9000\", namespace=\"default\", cr_name=\"my-interpreter\")` is initialized without `base_url`\n- **WHEN** the base URL is constructed\n- **THEN** `self.base_url` SHALL be `http://router:9000/v1/namespaces/default/code-interpreters/my-interpreter/invocations/`\n\n#### Scenario: Explicit base URL overrides construction\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient(base_url=\"http://custom:8080/custom/path/\")` is provided\n- **WHEN** initialization completes\n- **THEN** `self.base_url` SHALL be `http://custom:8080/custom/path/` without any router-based construction\n\n### Requirement: Control plane session creation and deletion\nThe system SHALL create sessions via POST to control plane API and delete via DELETE with 404 tolerance.\n\n#### Scenario: Create session returns session ID\n- **GIVEN** `ControlPlaneClient(base_url=\"http://wm:8080\")` is initialized\n- **WHEN** `create_session(name=\"test\", namespace=\"dev\", ttl=1800, metadata={\"key\": \"value\"})` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST `http://wm:8080/v1/code-interpreter` with JSON body containing all parameters and return the `sessionId` from response\n\n#### Scenario: Create session missing session ID in response\n- **GIVEN** the control plane POST succeeds but response JSON lacks `sessionId` field\n- **WHEN** the response is parsed\n- **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError` indicating missing `sessionId`\n\n#### Scenario: Delete session success\n- **GIVEN** `delete_session(\"session-123\")` is called and server returns 200 or 204\n- **WHEN** the response is processed\n- **THEN** the method SHALL return `True`\n\n#### Scenario: Delete session 404 treated as success\n- **GIVEN** `delete_session(\"session-404\")` is called and server returns 404\n- **WHEN** the response is received\n- **THEN** the method SHALL return `True` (session already deleted)\n\n#### Scenario: Delete session other failure\n- **GIVEN** `delete_session(\"session-err\")` is called and server returns 500\n- **WHEN** the error occurs\n- **THEN** the method SHALL log the error and return `False`\n\n### Requirement: Verbose mode logging\nThe system SHALL support verbose mode for debug logging across client operations.\n\n#### Scenario: Verbose mode enabled\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(verbose=True)` is initialized\n- **WHEN** operations like command execution or file transfers occur\n- **THEN** the client SHALL log debug-level messages including request details, response status, and timing information\n\n#### Scenario: Verbose mode disabled\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(verbose=False)` is initialized (default)\n- **WHEN** operations occur\n- **THEN** the client SHALL log only INFO-level and above messages (errors, warnings, info)\n\n### Requirement: TTL parameter handling\nThe system SHALL use the TTL parameter when creating sessions for session expiration control.\n\n#### Scenario: Custom TTL for session creation\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(ttl=7200)` is initialized without `session_id`\n- **WHEN** a new session is created via control plane\n- **THEN** the request body SHALL include `ttl: 7200` to set session expiration to 2 hours\n\n#### Scenario: Default TTL when not specified\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is initialized without explicit TTL\n- **WHEN** a new session is created\n- **THEN** the request body SHALL include `ttl: 3600` (default 1 hour)\n\n### Requirement: Namespace parameter propagation\nThe system SHALL propagate namespace parameter through control plane and data plane URL construction.\n\n#### Scenario: Custom namespace in constructor\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(namespace=\"production\")` is initialized\n- **WHEN** session is created and data plane is initialized\n- **THEN** the control plane request SHALL include `namespace: \"production\"` and data plane base URL SHALL include `/namespaces/production/`\n\n#### Scenario: Default namespace\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is initialized without namespace\n- **WHEN** initialization completes\n- **THEN** namespace SHALL default to `\"default\"` in both control plane request and data plane URL\n\n### Requirement: Metadata support in session creation\nThe system SHALL support optional metadata dictionary when creating sessions.\n\n#### Scenario: Session with metadata\n- **GIVEN** `ControlPlaneClient.create_session(name=\"test\", namespace=\"dev\", metadata={\"owner\": \"user1\", \"purpose\": \"data-analysis\"})` is called\n- **WHEN** the request body is prepared\n- **THEN** the JSON SHALL include `metadata: {\"owner\": \"user1\", \"purpose\": \"data-analysis\"}`\n\n#### Scenario: Session without metadata\n- **GIVEN** `create_session(name=\"test\", namespace=\"dev\")` is called without metadata parameter\n- **WHEN** the request body is prepared\n- **THEN** the JSON SHALL include `metadata: null` or omit the metadata field\n\n## Acceptance Criteria Summary\n\n1. ✅ Client initialization resolves environment variables correctly\n2. ✅ Context manager protocol properly manages lifecycle\n3. ✅ Data plane failures trigger cleanup before re-raising\n4. ✅ Commands execute with proper timeout and error handling\n5. ✅ Code execution handles Python specially via file operations\n6. ✅ File operations (write, upload, download, list) work correctly\n7. ✅ HTTP sessions use connection pooling\n8. ✅ Logging configured with appropriate levels\n9. ✅ Session headers injected in all data plane requests\n10. ✅ Base URLs constructed correctly for data plane\n11. ✅ Control plane session create/delete work with 404 tolerance\n12. ✅ Verbose mode provides debug logging when enabled\n13. ✅ TTL and namespace parameters propagate correctly\n14. ✅ Optional metadata supported in session creation\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- `requests` library for HTTP client functionality\n- `PyJWT>=2.0.0` for JWT token handling (if needed)\n- `cryptography` for cryptographic operations (if needed)\n- Python >=3.10\n\n## References\n\n- Base Design: `python-sdk/design.md`\n- Base Specification: `python-sdk/spec.md`\n- AR: AR-027 — SDK CodeInterpreterClient","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md"},"error":"You must read file /home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md before overwriting it. Use the Read tool first","time":{"start":1775876759887,"end":1775876759892}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775876759925,"sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","part":{"id":"prt_d7a80e158001jX4kEEQ2nyqsHm","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d7a7fd09a00164Iv5jnKKgJxaQ","sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":26405,"input":6258,"output":5108,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":15039}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775876761006,"sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","part":{"id":"prt_d7a80e5ac001cbdzIKhZUpSn9P","messageID":"msg_d7a80e18b001SvQrpZT8wwLMqx","sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775876761777,"sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","part":{"id":"prt_d7a80e883001mJv1W36kWDc0Ne","messageID":"msg_d7a80e18b001SvQrpZT8wwLMqx","sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-765fdf1b842441b88ed44f700c0edac6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Specification: AR-026 — K8s/AgentCube Provider\n2: \n3: ## Module: `cmd/cli`\n4: \n5: ## Language: Python\n6: \n7: ## Size: M\n8: \n9: ## Delta Overview\n10: \n11: Implement dual provider support in the AgentCube CLI for deploying AI agents to Kubernetes: a standard provider using native Deployment and Service resources, and an AgentCube provider using the AgentRuntime custom resource (CR) for enhanced lifecycle management.\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: ## REQ-001: Provider selection via CLI flag\n16: \n17: ### Requirement: Provider parameter on commands\n18: \n19: System SHALL allow users to select the deployment target provider using the `--provider` flag on relevant commands (`publish`, `status`, `invoke`), with `agentcube` as the default provider.\n20: \n21: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n22: - `--provider` flag accepts `k8s` or `agentcube` values\n23: - Default value is `agentcube` when not specified\n24: - Invalid provider values trigger error messages with valid options\n25: - Provider selection is propagated to runtime classes\n26: \n27: **Scenarios:**\n28: \n29: #### Scenario 1.1: Default provider value\n30: - **GIVEN** the user runs `publish` without the `--provider` flag\n31: - **WHEN** the Typer command callback runs\n32: - **THEN** the `provider` parameter SHALL default to `\"agentcube\"`\n33: \n34: #### Scenario 1.2: Valid provider selection - k8s\n35: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `--provider k8s`\n36: - **WHEN** the command executes\n37: - **THEN** the system SHALL route deployment operations to `KubernetesProvider`\n38: \n39: #### Scenario 1.3: Valid provider selection - agentcube\n40: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `--provider agentcube`\n41: - **WHEN** the command executes\n42: - **THEN** the system SHALL route deployment operations to `AgentCubeProvider`\n43: \n44: #### Scenario 1.4: Invalid provider value\n45: - **GIVEN** the user specifies `--provider invalid`\n46: - **WHEN** the command validates the provider parameter\n47: - **THEN** the system SHALL print an error message indicating valid options are `k8s` or `agentcube` and exit with code `1`\n48: \n49: ---\n50: \n51: ## REQ-002: Kubernetes provider — Deployment creation\n52: \n53: ### Requirement: Create Kubernetes Deployment resource\n54: \n55: System SHALL create a Kubernetes `Deployment` resource with configurable replicas, container port, and optional environment variables when using the `k8s` provider.\n56: \n57: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n58: - Creates Deployment with sanitized name from agent_name\n59: - Supports configurable replicas (default: 1)\n60: - Sets container image from image_url\n61: - Configures container port\n62: - Supports custom entrypoint command\n63: - Supports environment variables\n64: - Creates namespace if it doesn't exist\n65: \n66: **Scenarios:**\n67: \n68: #### Scenario 2.1: Minimal deployment creation\n69: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `k8s`, `replicas` is `1` (default), and no env_vars are provided\n70: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider.deploy_agent` is called with `agent_name`, `image_url`, and `port`\n71: - **THEN** the system SHALL create a Deployment with:\n72:   - `metadata.name` sanitized from `agent_name` via `_sanitize_name`\n73:   - `spec.replicas` set to `1`\n74:   - `spec.template.spec.containers[0].image` set to `image_url`\n75:   - `spec.template.spec.containers[0].ports[0].containerPort` set to `port`\n76:   - No environment variables in the container spec\n77: \n78: #### Scenario 2.2: Deployment with replicas and env vars\n79: - **GIVEN** `replicas` is `3` and `env_vars` is `{\"API_KEY\": \"secret\", \"DEBUG\": \"true\"}`\n80: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider.deploy_agent` is called\n81: - **THEN** the system SHALL create a Deployment with `spec.replicas` set to `3` and container `env` array containing both key-value pairs\n82: \n83: #### Scenario 2.3: Deployment with custom entrypoint\n84: - **GIVEN** `entrypoint` is `[\"python\", \"-u\", \"main.py\"]`\n85: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider.deploy_agent` is called\n86: - **THEN** the container spec SHALL set `command` to the provided list\n87: \n88: #### Scenario 2.4: Name sanitization for K8s compliance\n89: - **GIVEN** `agent_name` is `my-agent-prod_v2.0`\n90: - **WHEN** `_sanitize_name` processes the name\n91: - **THEN** the result SHALL conform to Kubernetes naming rules (lowercase alphanumeric, hyphens, max 253 chars), e.g., `my-agent-prod-v2-0`\n92: \n93: #### Scenario 2.5: Namespace creation\n94: - **GIVEN** `namespace` is provided and does not exist\n95: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider` initializes or deploys\n96: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `_ensure_namespace` which creates the namespace if missing via the Kubernetes API\n97: \n98: ---\n99: \n100: ## REQ-003: Kubernetes provider — Service creation\n101: \n102: ### Requirement: Create NodePort Service\n103: \n104: System SHALL create a NodePort Service exposing the deployment, with either a user-specified NodePort or an auto-assigned port in the valid range.\n105: \n106: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n107: - Creates Service of type NodePort\n108: - Supports user-specified NodePort (30000-32767)\n109: - Auto-assigns NodePort if not specified\n110: - Service selector matches deployment labels\n111: - Constructs service URL with NodePort\n112: \n113: **Scenarios:**\n114: \n115: #### Scenario 3.1: Service with user-specified NodePort\n116: - **GIVEN** `node_port` is `30080`\n117: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider._create_service` is called\n118: - **THEN** the Service SHALL have `spec.ports[0].nodePort` set to `30080`\n119: \n120: #### Scenario 3.2: Service with auto-assigned NodePort\n121: - **GIVEN** `node_port` is `None`\n122: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider._create_service` is called\n123: - **THEN** the Service SHALL omit the `nodePort` field, allowing Kubernetes to auto-assign a port in the 30000-32767 range\n124: \n125: #### Scenario 3.3: Service selector matches deployment\n126: - **GIVEN** the deployment was created with sanitized name `my-agent`\n127: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider._create_service` runs\n128: - **THEN** the Service SHALL have `spec.selector` matching the deployment labels, typically including `app: my-agent`\n129: \n130: #### Scenario 3.4: Service URL construction\n131: - **GIVEN** the Service has `nodePort` `30080`\n132: - **WHEN** deployment completes successfully\n133: - **THEN** the result SHALL include `service_url` as `http://localhost:30080`\n134: \n135: ---\n136: \n137: ## REQ-004: Kubernetes provider — Rollout readiness\n138: \n139: ### Requirement: Wait for deployment readiness\n140: \n141: System SHALL wait for the deployment to reach a ready state before considering the deployment complete, with a configurable timeout.\n142: \n143: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n144: - Polls deployment status every 2 seconds\n145: - Checks that readyReplicas equals replicas\n146: - Returns without error when all replicas are ready\n147: - Raises TimeoutError if deployment doesn't become ready within timeout\n148: \n149: **Scenarios:**\n150: \n151: #### Scenario 4.1: Successful rollout within timeout\n152: - **GIVEN** the deployment is created and pods become ready within 60 seconds\n153: - **WHEN** `wait_for_deployment_ready(name=\"my-agent\", timeout=120)` is called\n154: - **THEN** the method SHALL return without error after all replicas are ready\n155: \n156: #### Scenario 4.2: Rollout timeout\n157: - **GIVEN** the deployment fails to become ready after 120 seconds\n158: - **WHEN** `wait_for_deployment_ready(name=\"my-agent\", timeout=120)` is called\n159: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `TimeoutError` indicating the deployment did not become ready in time\n160: \n161: #### Scenario 4.3: Readiness polling\n162: - **GIVEN** `wait_for_deployment_ready` is polling\n163: - **WHEN** checking deployment status\n164: - **THEN** the system SHALL query the deployment status every 2 seconds and check that `status.readyReplicas` equals `spec.replicas`\n165: \n166: ---\n167: \n168: ## REQ-005: Kubernetes provider — Status retrieval\n169: \n170: ### Requirement: Retrieve deployment status\n171: \n172: System SHALL retrieve and report deployment status including replica counts, pod states, and service URL when using the `k8s` provider.\n173: \n174: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n175: - Retrieves deployment status from Kubernetes API\n176: - Reports replica counts (replicas, ready_replicas, available_replicas)\n177: - Reports NodePort and service URL\n178: - Handles various deployment states (running, degraded, not_found)\n179: \n180: **Scenarios:**\n181: \n182: #### Scenario 5.1: Running deployment status\n183: - **GIVEN** a deployment with 3 replicas is running, all pods are ready, and service has NodePort 30080\n184: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider.get_agent_status(agent_name)` is called\n185: - **THEN** the result SHALL include:\n186:   - `status: \"running\"`\n187:   - `replicas: 3`\n188:   - `ready_replicas: 3`\n189:   - `available_replicas: 3`\n190:   - `node_port: 30080`\n191:   - `service_url: \"http://localhost:30080\"`\n192: \n193: #### Scenario 5.2: Deployment with unavailable pods\n194: - **GIVEN** a deployment with 2 replicas has 1 ready and 1 `CrashLoopBackOff`\n195: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider.get_agent_status` is called\n196: - **THEN** the result SHALL include `status: \"degraded\"` or `\"partial\"` and indicate the pod states\n197: \n198: #### Scenario 5.3: Non-existent deployment\n199: - **GIVEN** no deployment exists for `agent_name`\n200: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider.get_agent_status` is called\n201: - **THEN** the result SHALL include `status: \"not_found\"`\n202: \n203: ---\n204: \n205: ## REQ-006: Kubernetes provider — Deletion\n206: \n207: ### Requirement: Delete deployment and service\n208: \n209: System SHALL delete both the Deployment and Service resources when removing an agent deployed via the `k8s` provider.\n210: \n211: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n212: - Deletes both Deployment and Service resources\n213: - Ignores 404 errors if resources don't exist\n214: - Returns success status with deployment and namespace information\n215: \n216: **Scenarios:**\n217: \n218: #### Scenario 6.1: Successful deletion\n219: - **GIVEN** a deployment and service exist for `agent_name`\n220: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider.delete_agent(agent_name)` is called\n221: - **THEN** the system SHALL delete both resources and return `{\"status\": \"deleted\", \"deployment_name\": <sanitized-name>, \"namespace\": <namespace>}`\n222: \n223: #### Scenario 6.2: Partial deletion tolerance\n224: - **GIVEN** only the Service exists (Deployment already deleted)\n225: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider.delete_agent` is called\n226: - **THEN** the system SHALL delete the Service, ignore the 404 error for the Deployment, and return success\n227: \n228: ---\n229: \n230: ## REQ-007: AgentCube provider — AgentRuntime CR creation\n231: \n232: ### Requirement: Create AgentRuntime custom resource\n233: \n234: System SHALL create or update an AgentRuntime custom resource in the `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1` API group when using the `agentcube` provider.\n235: \n236: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n237: - Creates AgentRuntime CR with sanitized name\n238: - Sets image, port, sessionTimeout, maxSessionDuration\n239: - Supports readiness probe configuration\n240: - Supports custom environment variables\n241: - Auto-injects WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL and ROUTER_URL if not provided\n242: - Configures imagePullSecrets\n243: - Creates namespace if it doesn't exist\n244: \n245: **Scenarios:**\n246: \n247: #### Scenario 7.1: Minimal AgentRuntime creation\n248: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `agentcube` and metadata contains `image_url` and `port`\n249: - **WHEN** `AgentCubeProvider.deploy_agent_runtime` is called\n250: - **THEN** the system SHALL create an AgentRuntime CR with:\n251:   - `metadata.name` sanitized from `agent_name`\n252:   - `spec.image` set to `image_url`\n253:   - `spec.port` set to `port`\n254:   - `spec.sessionTimeout` set to `\"15m\"`\n255:   - `spec.maxSessionDuration` set to `\"8h\"`\n256: \n257: #### Scenario 7.2: AgentRuntime with readiness probe\n258: - **GIVEN** metadata includes `readiness_probe_path: \"/health\"` and `readiness_probe_port: 8080`\n259: - **WHEN** `AgentCubeProvider.deploy_agent_runtime` is called\n260: - **THEN** the CR SHALL include `spec.readinessProbe` with `httpGet.path: \"/health\"` and `httpGet.port: 8080`\n261: \n262: #### Scenario 7.3: AgentRuntime with custom env vars\n263: - **GIVEN** `env_vars` is `{\"WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL\": \"http://wm:8080\", \"ROUTER_URL\": \"http://router:8080\"}`\n264: - **WHEN** `AgentCubeProvider.deploy_agent_runtime` is called\n265: - **THEN** the CR SHALL include these in `spec.env`\n266: \n267: #### Scenario 7.4: Auto-inject WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL and ROUTER_URL\n268: - **GIVEN** `env_vars` is `None` but `workload_manager_url` and `router_url` parameters are provided\n269: - **WHEN** `AgentCubeProvider.deploy_agent_runtime` is called\n270: - **THEN** the system SHALL inject `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` and `ROUTER_URL` into `spec.env` from the parameters or environment variables\n271: \n272: #### Scenario 7.5: Image pull secret configuration\n273: - **GIVEN** the AgentRuntime CR is being created\n274: - **WHEN** `AgentCubeProvider.deploy_agent_runtime` runs\n275: - **THEN** the CR SHALL include `spec.imagePullSecrets: [{\"name\": \"default-secret\"}]`\n276: \n277: #### Scenario 7.6: Namespace creation for AgentCube provider\n278: - **GIVEN** `namespace` is provided and does not exist\n279: - **WHEN** `AgentCubeProvider` initializes or deploys\n280: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `_ensure_namespace` which creates the namespace if missing\n281: \n282: ---\n283: \n284: ## REQ-008: AgentCube provider — AgentRuntime update\n285: \n286: ### Requirement: Update existing AgentRuntime CR\n287: \n288: System SHALL support updating an existing AgentRuntime CR when re-publishing, using strategic merge patch.\n289: \n290: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n291: - Patches existing CR with new values\n292: - Preserves fields not being updated\n293: - Uses strategic merge patch for safe updates\n294: \n295: **Scenarios:**\n296: \n297: #### Scenario 8.1: Update existing CR\n298: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime CR exists for `agent_name` with `image: \"old:v1\"`\n299: - **WHEN** `deploy_agent_runtime` is called with a new `image_url: \"new:v2\"`\n300: - **THEN** the system SHALL patch the existing CR with the new image while preserving other fields\n301: \n302: #### Scenario 8.2: Update with readiness probe addition\n303: - **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime CR without a readiness probe\n304: - **WHEN** `deploy_agent_runtime` is called with `readiness_probe_path` and `readiness_probe_port`\n305: - **THEN** the patched CR SHALL include the new `readinessProbe` configuration\n306: \n307: ---\n308: \n309: ## REQ-009: AgentCube provider — Status retrieval\n310: \n311: ### Requirement: Retrieve AgentRuntime status\n312: \n313: System SHALL retrieve AgentRuntime status from the CR's `status` field, reporting agent endpoint and runtime state.\n314: \n315: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n316: - Reads AgentRuntime CR from Kubernetes API\n317: - Reports status from CR's status field\n318: - Handles cases where status is not yet populated\n319: - Returns appropriate status for non-existent CRs\n320: \n321: **Scenarios:**\n322: \n323: #### Scenario 9.1: Running AgentRuntime with status\n324: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime CR exists with `status.phase: \"Running\"` and `status.agentEndpoint: \"http://service:8080\"`\n325: - **WHEN** `StatusRuntime._get_cr_k8s_status` is called\n326: - **THEN** the result SHALL include:\n327:   - `status: \"running\"`\n328:   - `agent_endpoint: \"http://service:8080\"`\n329:   - `phase: \"Running\"`\n330: \n331: #### Scenario 9.2: AgentRuntime created but no status yet\n332: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime CR exists but has no `status` field populated yet\n333: - **WHEN** `StatusRuntime._get_cr_k8s_status` is called\n334: - **THEN** the result SHALL include `status: \"created_no_status\"`\n335: \n336: #### Scenario 9.3: AgentRuntime not found\n337: - **GIVEN** no AgentRuntime CR exists for `agent_name`\n338: - **WHEN** `StatusRuntime._get_cr_k8s_status` is called\n339: - **THEN** the result SHALL include `status: \"not_found_in_k8s\"`\n340: \n341: ---\n342: \n343: ## REQ-010: Publish runtime — Provider routing\n344: \n345: ### Requirement: Route publish operations to appropriate provider\n346: \n347: System SHALL route `publish` command operations to the appropriate provider class based on the `--provider` flag.\n348: \n349: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n350: - Routes to KubernetesProvider for --provider k8s\n351: - Routes to AgentCubeProvider for --provider agentcube\n352: - Prepares image appropriately for each provider\n353: \n354: **Scenarios:**\n355: \n356: #### Scenario 10.1: Publish with k8s provider\n357: - **GIVEN** the user runs `publish --provider k8s` with valid workspace and image\n358: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime.publish` executes\n359: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `PublishRuntime._publish_k8s` which uses `KubernetesProvider.deploy_agent`\n360: \n361: #### Scenario 10.2: Publish with agentcube provider\n362: - **GIVEN** the user runs `publish --provider agentcube` with valid workspace and image\n363: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime.publish` executes\n364: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `PublishRuntime._publish_cr_to_k8s` which uses `AgentCubeProvider.deploy_agent_runtime`\n365: \n366: #### Scenario 10.3: Publish image preparation for k8s\n367: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `k8s` and `image_url` is provided\n368: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime._prepare_image_for_publishing` runs\n369: - **THEN** the system SHALL use the provided `image_url` directly for Kubernetes deployment\n370: \n371: #### Scenario 10.4: Publish image preparation for agentcube\n372: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `agentcube` and `build_mode` is `local`\n373: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime._prepare_image_for_publishing` runs\n374: - **THEN** the system SHALL either push the local image to a registry or use the local image URL depending on configuration\n375: \n376: ---\n377: \n378: ## REQ-011: Status runtime — Provider routing\n379: \n380: ### Requirement: Route status queries to appropriate provider\n381: \n382: System SHALL route `status` command queries to the appropriate provider class based on the `--provider` flag and deployment type.\n383: \n384: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n385: - Routes to KubernetesProvider for --provider k8s\n386: - Routes to AgentCubeProvider for --provider agentcube\n387: - Auto-detects provider from metadata when --provider not specified\n388: \n389: **Scenarios:**\n390: \n391: #### Scenario 11.1: Status with k8s provider\n392: - **GIVEN** the user runs `status --provider k8s`\n393: - **WHEN** `StatusRuntime.get_status` executes\n394: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `StatusRuntime._get_k8s_status` which uses `KubernetesProvider.get_agent_status`\n395: \n396: #### Scenario 11.2: Status with agentcube provider\n397: - **GIVEN** the user runs `status --provider agentcube`\n398: - **WHEN** `StatusRuntime.get_status` executes\n399: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `StatusRuntime._get_cr_k8s_status` which uses `AgentCubeProvider.get_agent_runtime`\n400: \n401: #### Scenario 11.3: Auto-detect provider from metadata\n402: - **GIVEN** metadata has `k8s_deployment.type: \"AgentRuntime\"` and user runs `status` without `--provider`\n403: - **WHEN** `StatusRuntime.get_status` executes\n404: - **THEN** the system SHALL automatically use the AgentCube provider path\n405: \n406: ---\n407: \n408: ## REQ-012: Invoke runtime — Provider routing\n409: \n410: ### Requirement: Route invoke HTTP requests based on provider\n411: \n412: System SHALL route `invoke` command HTTP requests based on the agent's deployment type and provider, using appropriate URL patterns.\n413: \n414: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n415: - Routes to direct HTTP invocation for k8s provider\n416: - Routes to AgentCube invocation endpoint for agentcube provider\n417: - Rewrites URL for AgentRuntime deployments\n418: - Includes session header when available\n419: \n420: **Scenarios:**\n421: \n422: #### Scenario 12.1: Invoke with k8s provider\n423: - **GIVEN** the agent was deployed with `provider=k8s` and has `node_port: 30080`\n424: - **WHEN** `InvokeRuntime.invoke` runs with `provider=\"k8s\"`\n425: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `_direct_http_invocation` targeting `http://localhost:30080` with the JSON payload\n426: \n427: #### Scenario 12.2: Invoke with agentcube provider and CR endpoint\n428: - **GIVEN** the agent was deployed with `provider=agentcube` and metadata has `agent_endpoint: \"http://service:8080\"`\n429: - **WHEN** `InvokeRuntime.invoke` runs with `provider=\"agentcube\"`\n430: - **THEN** the system SHALL call `_invoke_agent_via_agentcube` targeting the agent endpoint with session header\n431: \n432: #### Scenario 12.3: Invoke URL rewrite for AgentRuntime\n433: - **GIVEN** metadata has `k8s_deployment.type: \"AgentRuntime\"` and base endpoint from metadata\n434: - **WHEN** `InvokeRuntime._invoke_agent_via_agentcube` constructs the URL\n435: - **THEN** the system SHALL rewrite to `{base}/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agent-runtimes/{agent_name}/invocations/`\n436: \n437: #### Scenario 12.4: Session header inclusion\n438: - **GIVEN** metadata contains `session_id: \"abc123\"`\n439: - **WHEN** `InvokeRuntime.invoke` sends the request\n440: - **THEN** the HTTP headers SHALL include `X-Agentcube-Session-Id: abc123`\n441: \n442: ---\n443: \n444: ## REQ-013: Error handling for provider operations\n445: \n446: ### Requirement: Provide clear error messages for provider failures\n447: \n448: System SHALL provide clear error messages for provider-specific failures, including K8s API errors, missing CRDs, and invalid configurations.\n449: \n450: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n451: - Surfaces Kubernetes client initialization failures\n452: - Detects missing AgentRuntime CRD\n453: - Validates NodePort range\n454: - Validates required AgentCube URLs\n455: - Provides user-friendly error messages\n456: \n457: **Scenarios:**\n458: \n459: #### Scenario 13.1: Kubernetes client initialization failure\n460: - **GIVEN** the kubeconfig is invalid or cluster is unreachable\n461: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider` or `AgentCubeProvider` initializes\n462: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise a descriptive error indicating Kubernetes connection failure and suggest checking kubeconfig\n463: \n464: #### Scenario 13.2: AgentRuntime CRD not installed\n465: - **GIVEN** the AgentRuntime CRD is not installed in the cluster\n466: - **WHEN** `AgentCubeProvider.deploy_agent_runtime` attempts to create the CR\n467: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise an error indicating the CRD is not found and suggest installing the AgentCube operator\n468: \n469: #### Scenario 13.3: Invalid NodePort range\n470: - **GIVEN** `node_port` is `40000` (outside 30000-32767)\n471: - **WHEN** `KubernetesProvider._create_service` attempts to create the service\n472: - **THEN** Kubernetes API SHALL reject with validation error, which the system SHALL surface as a user-friendly message\n473: \n474: #### Scenario 13.4: Missing required AgentCube URLs\n475: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `agentcube` and metadata lacks `router_url` or `workload_manager_url`\n476: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime._publish_cr_to_k8s` validates prerequisites\n477: - **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError` requiring both fields in `agent_metadata.yaml`\n478: \n479: ---\n480: \n481: ## REQ-014: Metadata updates after deployment\n482: \n483: ### Requirement: Update metadata with deployment information\n484: \n485: System SHALL update workspace metadata with deployment information after successful publish operations, varying by provider.\n486: \n487: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n488: - Updates k8s_deployment field for k8s provider\n489: - Updates k8s_deployment and agent_id for agentcube provider\n490: - Preserves other metadata fields\n491: \n492: **Scenarios:**\n493: \n494: #### Scenario 14.1: K8s provider metadata update\n495: - **GIVEN** a deployment succeeds with `node_port: 30080`\n496: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime._update_publish_metadata` runs\n497: - **THEN** metadata SHALL be updated with:\n498:   - `k8s_deployment.type: \"Deployment\"`\n499:   - `k8s_deployment.name: <sanitized-name>`\n500:   - `k8s_deployment.namespace: <namespace>`\n501:   - `k8s_deployment.node_port: 30080`\n502:   - `k8s_deployment.service_url: \"http://localhost:30080\"`\n503: \n504: #### Scenario 14.2: AgentCube provider metadata update\n505: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime CR is created successfully\n506: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime._update_publish_metadata` runs\n507: - **THEN** metadata SHALL be updated with:\n508:   - `k8s_deployment.type: \"AgentRuntime\"`\n509:   - `k8s_deployment.name: <sanitized-name>`\n510:   - `k8s_deployment.namespace: <namespace>`\n511:   - `agent_id: <cr-name>` (optional, if assigned by controller)\n512: \n513: ---\n514: \n515: ## REQ-015: Namespace parameter handling\n516: \n517: ### Requirement: Support namespace specification and defaults\n518: \n519: System SHALL support explicit namespace specification via `--namespace` flag for all provider operations, with intelligent defaults.\n520: \n521: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n522: - Supports explicit namespace via --namespace flag\n523: - Defaults to \"default\" namespace when not specified\n524: - Maintains namespace consistency across commands\n525: \n526: **Scenarios:**\n527: \n528: #### Scenario 15.1: Explicit namespace for publish\n529: - **GIVEN** the user runs `publish --namespace production`\n530: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime.publish` executes\n531: - **THEN** the system SHALL deploy to the `production` namespace\n532: \n533: #### Scenario 15.2: Default namespace when omitted\n534: - **GIVEN** the user runs `publish` without `--namespace`\n535: - **WHEN** `PublishRuntime.publish` executes\n536: - **THEN** the system SHALL use `default` namespace for both providers\n537: \n538: #### Scenario 15.3: Namespace consistency across commands\n539: - **GIVEN** an agent was published to namespace `staging`\n540: - **WHEN** user runs `status` or `invoke` without `--namespace`\n541: - **THEN** the system SHALL read the namespace from metadata's `k8s_deployment.namespace` field\n542: \n543: ---\n544: \n545: ## Data Model Changes\n546: \n547: ### `KubernetesProvider` class\n548: \n549: ```python\n550: class KubernetesProvider:\n551:     def __init__(\n552:         self,\n553:         namespace: str = \"default\",\n554:         verbose: bool = False,\n555:         kubeconfig: Optional[str] = None,\n556:     ) -> None: ...\n557: \n558:     def _ensure_namespace(self) -> None: ...\n559: \n560:     def deploy_agent(\n561:         self,\n562:         agent_name: str,\n563:         image_url: str,\n564:         port: int,\n565:         entrypoint: Optional[str] = None,\n566:         replicas: int = 1,\n567:         node_port: Optional[int] = None,\n568:         env_vars: Optional[Dict[str, str]] = None,\n569:     ) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n570: \n571:     def _create_deployment(\n572:         self,\n573:         name: str,\n574:         image_url: str,\n575:         port: int,\n576:         entrypoint: Optional[str],\n577:         replicas: int,\n578:         env_vars: Optional[Dict[str, str]],\n579:     ) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n580: \n581:     def _create_service(self, name: str, port: int, node_port: Optional[int]) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n582: \n583:     def wait_for_deployment_ready(self, name: str, timeout: int = 120) -> None: ...\n584: \n585:     def get_agent_status(self, agent_name: str) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n586: \n587:     def delete_agent(self, agent_name: str) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n588: \n589:     def _sanitize_name(self, name: str) -> str: ...\n590: ```\n591: \n592: ### `AgentCubeProvider` class\n593: \n594: ```python\n595: class AgentCubeProvider:\n596:     def __init__(\n597:         self,\n598:         namespace: str = \"default\",\n599:         verbose: bool = False,\n600:         kubeconfig: Optional[str] = None,\n601:     ) -> None: ...\n602: \n603:     def _ensure_namespace(self) -> None: ...\n604: \n605:     def deploy_agent_runtime(\n606:         self,\n607:         agent_name: str,\n608:         image_url: str,\n609:         port: int,\n610:         entrypoint: Optional[str] = None,\n611:         env_vars: Optional[Dict[str, str]] = None,\n612:         workload_manager_url: Optional[str] = None,\n613:         router_url: Optional[str] = None,\n614:         readiness_probe_path: Optional[str] = None,\n615:         readiness_probe_port: Optional[int] = None,\n616:     ) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n617: \n618:     def _sanitize_name(self, name: str) -> str: ...\n619: \n620:     def get_agent_runtime(self, name: str, namespace: str) -> Optional[Dict[str, Any]]: ...\n621: ```\n622: \n623: ### CR API constants\n624: \n625: ```python\n626: AGENTRUNTIME_GROUP = \"runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh\"\n627: AGENTRUNTIME_VERSION = \"v1alpha1\"\n628: AGENTRUNTIME_PLURAL = \"agentruntimes\"\n629: ```\n630: \n631: ### `PublishRuntime` enhancements\n632: \n633: ```python\n634: class PublishRuntime:\n635:     def publish(self, workspace_path: Path, **options: Any) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n636:     def _publish_cr_to_k8s(self, workspace_path: Path, metadata, **options: Any) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n637:     def _publish_k8s(self, workspace_path: Path, metadata, **options: Any) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n638:     def _prepare_image_for_publishing(self, workspace_path: Path, metadata, options: Dict[str, Any]) -> str: ...\n639:     def _update_publish_metadata(self, workspace_path: Path, agent_info: Dict[str, Any]) -> None: ...\n640: ```\n641: \n642: ### `StatusRuntime` enhancements\n643: \n644: ```python\n645: class StatusRuntime:\n646:     def get_status(self, workspace_path: Path, provider: Optional[str] = None) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n647:     def _get_k8s_status(self, metadata) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n648:     def _get_cr_k8s_status(self, metadata) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n649: ```\n650: \n651: ### `InvokeRuntime` enhancements\n652: \n653: ```python\n654: class InvokeRuntime:\n655:     def invoke(self, workspace_path: Path, payload: Dict[str, Any], headers: Optional[Dict[str, str]] = None) -> Any: ...\n656:     def _validate_invoke_prerequisites(self, workspace_path: Path) -> Tuple[Any, str, str]: ...\n657:     async def _invoke_agent_via_agentcube(self, agent_id: str, payload: Dict[str, Any], headers: Optional[Dict[str, str]], endpoint: str, workspace_path: Path) -> Any: ...\n658:     async def _direct_http_invocation(self, endpoint: str, payload: Dict[str, Any], headers: Optional[Dict[str, str]], workspace_path: Path) -> Dict[str, Any]: ...\n659: ```\n660: \n661: ---\n662: \n663: ## Testing Requirements\n664: \n665: ### Unit Test Scenarios\n666: \n667: #### Scenario UT-1: Test KubernetesProvider deployment\n668: - **GIVEN** a mocked Kubernetes API client\n669: - **WHEN** tests run\n670: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n671:   - Minimal deployment creation\n672:   - Deployment with replicas and env vars\n673:   - Deployment with custom entrypoint\n674:   - Name sanitization\n675:   - Namespace creation\n676: \n677: #### Scenario UT-2: Test KubernetesProvider service\n678: - **GIVEN** a mocked Kubernetes API client\n679: - **WHEN** tests run\n680: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n681:   - Service with user-specified NodePort\n682:   - Service with auto-assigned NodePort\n683:   - Service selector matching deployment\n684:   - Service URL construction\n685: \n686: #### Scenario UT-3: Test KubernetesProvider status and deletion\n687: - **GIVEN** a mocked Kubernetes API client\n688: - **WHEN** tests run\n689: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n690:   - Running deployment status\n691:   - Deployment with unavailable pods\n692:   - Non-existent deployment\n693:   - Successful deletion\n694:   - Partial deletion tolerance\n695: \n696: #### Scenario UT-4: Test AgentCubeProvider\n697: - **GIVEN** a mocked Kubernetes API client\n698: - **WHEN** tests run\n699: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n700:   - Minimal AgentRuntime creation\n701:   - AgentRuntime with readiness probe\n702:   - AgentRuntime with custom env vars\n703:   - Auto-inject WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL and ROUTER_URL\n704:   - Image pull secret configuration\n705:   - AgentRuntime update\n706:   - Status retrieval scenarios\n707: \n708: #### Scenario UT-5: Test provider routing\n709: - **GIVEN** mocked provider instances\n710: - **WHEN** tests run\n711: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n712:   - Publish routing to k8s provider\n713:   - Publish routing to agentcube provider\n714:   - Status routing to k8s provider\n715:   - Status routing to agentcube provider\n716:   - Auto-detect provider from metadata\n717: \n718: #### Scenario UT-6: Test error handling\n719: - **GIVEN** various error conditions\n720: - **WHEN** tests run\n721: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n722:   - Kubernetes client initialization failure\n723:   - AgentRuntime CRD not installed\n724:   - Invalid NodePort range\n725:   - Missing required AgentCube URLs\n726: \n727: ### Integration Test Scenarios\n728: \n729: #### Scenario IT-1: End-to-end k8s provider workflow\n730: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster with kubectl configured\n731: - **WHEN** user runs:\n732:   1. `pack --agent-name my-k8s-agent --provider k8s`\n733:   2. `build`\n734:   3. `publish --provider k8s --node-port 30080`\n735:   4. `status --provider k8s`\n736:   5. `invoke --provider k8s --payload '{\"test\": \"data\"}'`\n737: - **THEN** each operation SHALL:\n738:   - Create Deployment and Service\n739:   - Report correct status\n740:   - Successfully invoke the agent\n741:   - Clean up on deletion\n742: \n743: #### Scenario IT-2: End-to-end agentcube provider workflow\n744: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster with AgentRuntime CRD installed\n745: - **WHEN** user runs:\n746:   1. `pack --agent-name my-ac-agent --provider agentcube`\n747:   2. `build`\n748:   3. `publish --provider agentcube`\n749:   4. `status --provider agentcube`\n750:   5. `invoke --provider agentcube --payload '{\"test\": \"data\"}'`\n751: - **THEN** each operation SHALL:\n752:   - Create AgentRuntime CR\n753:   - Report correct status\n754:   - Successfully invoke the agent\n755: \n756: ---\n757: \n758: ## Acceptance Criteria\n759: \n760: ### Functional Acceptance Criteria - Provider Selection\n761: \n762: - [ ] --provider flag accepts k8s and agentcube values\n763: - [ ] Default provider is agentcube\n764: - [ ] Invalid provider values trigger error with valid options\n765: - [ ] Provider selection propagated to runtime classes\n766: \n767: ### Functional Acceptance Criteria - Kubernetes Provider\n768: \n769: - [ ] Creates Deployment with correct configuration\n770: - [ ] Creates Service of type NodePort\n771: - [ ] Supports user-specified and auto-assigned NodePort\n772: - [ ] Waits for deployment readiness with timeout\n773: - [ ] Retrieves deployment status correctly\n774: - [ ] Deletes Deployment and Service\n775: - [ ] Sanitizes names for K8s compliance\n776: \n777: ### Functional Acceptance Criteria - AgentCube Provider\n778: \n779: - [ ] Creates AgentRuntime CR with correct configuration\n780: - [ ] Supports readiness probe configuration\n781: - [ ] Supports custom environment variables\n782: - [ ] Auto-injects WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL and ROUTER_URL\n783: - [ ] Configures imagePullSecrets\n784: - [ ] Updates existing AgentRuntime CR\n785: - [ ] Retrieves AgentRuntime status correctly\n786: \n787: ### Functional Acceptance Criteria - Provider Routing\n788: \n789: - [ ] Publish routes to correct provider\n790: - [ ] Status routes to correct provider\n791: - [ ] Invoke routes to correct provider\n792: - [ ] Auto-detects provider from metadata\n793: \n794: ### Functional Acceptance Criteria - Error Handling\n795: \n796: - [ ] Kubernetes client initialization failures surfaced\n797: - [ ] Missing AgentRuntime CRD detected\n798: - [ ] Invalid NodePort range validated\n799: - [ ] Missing required AgentCube URLs validated\n800: \n801: ### Functional Acceptance Criteria - Metadata Updates\n802: \n803: - [ ] K8s provider updates k8s_deployment field\n804: - [ ] AgentCube provider updates k8s_deployment and agent_id\n805: - [ ] Other metadata fields preserved\n806: \n807: ### Functional Acceptance Criteria - Namespace Handling\n808: \n809: - [ ] Explicit namespace via --namespace flag works\n810: - [ ] Default namespace is \"default\"\n811: - [ ] Namespace consistency maintained across commands\n812: \n813: ### Non-Functional Acceptance Criteria\n814: \n815: - [ ] Provider operations complete within reasonable time\n816: - [ ] Error messages are clear and actionable\n817: - [ ] Unit tests cover all new methods with >= 90% coverage\n818: - [ ] Integration tests cover end-to-end workflows\n819: - [ ] Code follows existing patterns in cli-toolkit/design.md\n820: \n821: ---\n822: \n823: ## Implementation Notes\n824: \n825: ### Key Components\n826: \n827: 1. **KubernetesProvider** (`agentcube/services/k8s_provider.py`)\n828:    - Implements standard Kubernetes Deployment and Service management\n829:    - Handles name sanitization, namespace management, readiness checks\n830: \n831: 2. **AgentCubeProvider** (`agentcube/services/agentcube_provider.py`)\n832:    - Implements AgentRuntime CR management\n833:    - Auto-injects required environment variables\n834:    - Configures imagePullSecrets\n835: \n836: 3. **PublishRuntime** (`agentcube/runtime/publish_runtime.py`)\n837:    - Enhanced with provider routing\n838:    - Separate methods for k8s and agentcube deployment paths\n839: \n840: 4. **StatusRuntime** (`agentcube/runtime/status_runtime.py`)\n841:    - Enhanced with provider routing\n842:    - Separate methods for k8s and agentcube status retrieval\n843: \n844: 5. **InvokeRuntime** (`agentcube/runtime/invoke_runtime.py`)\n845:    - Enhanced with provider-specific URL construction\n846:    - Session header handling\n847: \n848: ### Key Algorithms\n849: \n850: #### Provider Factory Pattern\n851: ```python\n852: def get_provider(provider_type: str, namespace: str, verbose: bool) -> Union[KubernetesProvider, AgentCubeProvider]:\n853:     if provider_type == \"k8s\":\n854:         return KubernetesProvider(namespace=namespace, verbose=verbose)\n855:     elif provider_type == \"agentcube\":\n856:         return AgentCubeProvider(namespace=namespace, verbose=verbose)\n857:     else:\n858:         raise ValueError(f\"Invalid provider: {provider_type}\")\n859: ```\n860: \n861: #### Name Sanitization\n862: ```python\n863: def _sanitize_name(self, name: str) -> str:\n864:     # Convert to lowercase, replace invalid chars with hyphens, truncate to 253 chars\n865:     sanitized = re.sub(r'[^a-z0-9-]', '-', name.lower())\n866:     sanitized = sanitized.strip('-')\n867:     return sanitized[:253]\n868: ```\n869: \n870: #### Metadata-Driven Provider Detection\n871: ```python\n872: def detect_provider_from_metadata(metadata: AgentMetadata) -> str:\n873:     if metadata.k8s_deployment and metadata.k8s_deployment.get(\"type\") == \"AgentRuntime\":\n874:         return \"agentcube\"\n875:     return \"k8s\"  # or default\n876: ```\n877: \n878: ### Technical Constraints\n879: \n880: ### Requirement: Language and dependencies\n881: \n882: System SHALL use Python 3.10+ and the following dependencies:\n883: \n884: **Dependencies:**\n885: - `kubernetes>=28.0.0` for Kubernetes API client\n886: - `pydantic>=2.0.0` for data validation (already in base)\n887: - `pyyaml>=6.0` for YAML parsing (already in base)\n888: \n889: ### Requirement: File locations\n890: \n891: - KubernetesProvider implementation: `agentcube/services/k8s_provider.py`\n892: - AgentCubeProvider implementation: `agentcube/services/agentcube_provider.py`\n893: - Runtime enhancements: `agentcube/runtime/publish_runtime.py`, `agentcube/runtime/status_runtime.py`, `agentcube/runtime/invoke_runtime.py`\n894: \n895: ### Requirement: Configuration\n896: \n897: - Default namespace: `\"default\"`\n898: - Default NodePort: auto-assigned by Kubernetes (30000-32767)\n899: - Default replicas: `1`\n900: - Deployment readiness timeout: `120` seconds\n901: - AgentRuntime sessionTimeout: `\"15m\"`\n902: - AgentRuntime maxSessionDuration: `\"8h\"`\n903: \n904: ---\n905: \n906: ## Related Requirements\n907: \n908: - **AR-022:** CLI publish command (uses provider system)\n909: - **AR-023:** CLI invoke/status commands (use provider system)\n910: - **cli-toolkit/design.md:** Base design for KubernetesProvider and AgentCubeProvider\n911: - **cli-toolkit/spec.md:** Base specification for provider operations\n912: - **deployment/client-go.md:** Reference for AgentRuntime CR API\n\n(End of file - total 912 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Specification: AR-026 — K8s/AgentCube Provider\n\n## Module: `cmd/cli`\n\n## Language: Python\n\n## Size: M\n\n## Delta Overview\n\nImplement dual provider support in the AgentCube CLI for deploying AI agents to Kubernetes: a standard provider using native Deployment and Service resources, and an AgentCube provider using the AgentRuntime custom resource (CR) for enhanced lifecycle management.\n\n---\n\n## REQ-001: Provider selection via CLI flag\n\n### Requirement: Provider parameter on commands\n\nSystem SHALL allow users to select the deployment target provider using the `--provider` flag on relevant commands (`publish`, `status`, `invoke`), with `agentcube` as the default provider.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775876761758,"end":1775876761774}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775876761799,"sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","part":{"id":"prt_d7a80e8b1001hXScEV0bOcpzWs","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d7a80e18b001SvQrpZT8wwLMqx","sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":26528,"input":223,"output":66,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":26239}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775876767049,"sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","part":{"id":"prt_d7a80fd460017VAMVvVrTuc7Ka","messageID":"msg_d7a80e8dc001Yn2QYw0pn87m0a","sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775876827522,"sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","part":{"id":"prt_d7a81e8ef001BZN2u3BykE99fj","messageID":"msg_d7a80e8dc001Yn2QYw0pn87m0a","sessionID":"ses_2858038c6ffeGHCUxnXrn0aIPF","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-2d07dba0693f46558270c846cc7e102c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Delta Specification: AR-027 — SDK CodeInterpreterClient\n\n## AR Metadata\n- **AR ID**: AR-027\n- **Title**: SDK CodeInterpreterClient\n- **Module**: sdk-python\n- **Language**: Python\n- **Size**: M\n- **Status**: Implementation Required\n\n## Purpose\nThis delta specification defines implementation requirements for the `CodeInterpreterClient` class in the AgentCube Python SDK, focusing on session lifecycle management, code execution, file operations, and HTTP client interactions.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: CodeInterpreterClient initialization with environment variable resolution\nThe system SHALL resolve `workload_manager_url` from parameter or `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` environment variable, resolve `router_url` from parameter or `ROUTER_URL` environment variable (required), and resolve `auth_token` from parameter or `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token`.\n\n#### Scenario: All parameters provided explicitly\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(name=\"test\", namespace=\"dev\", ttl=1800, workload_manager_url=\"http://wm:8080\", router_url=\"http://router:9000\", auth_token=\"custom-token\")` is called\n- **WHEN** initialization completes\n- **THEN** the client SHALL use the provided `workload_manager_url`, `router_url`, and `auth_token` values directly\n\n#### Scenario: Workload Manager URL from environment\n- **GIVEN** environment variable `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` is set to `http://wm-default:8080`\n- **WHEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(router_url=\"http://router:9000\")` is called without `workload_manager_url`\n- **THEN** the client SHALL resolve `workload_manager_url` to `http://wm-default:8080`\n\n#### Scenario: Router URL missing required parameter\n- **GIVEN** neither `router_url` parameter nor `ROUTER_URL` environment variable is set\n- **WHEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is initialized\n- **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError` with message containing \"Router URL must be provided\"\n\n#### Scenario: Auth token from Kubernetes service account\n- **GIVEN** `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token` contains valid JWT token\n- **WHEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is called without `auth_token` parameter\n- **THEN** the client SHALL read and use the token from the file path via `read_token_from_file`\n\n#### Scenario: Service account token file missing\n- **GIVEN** `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token` does not exist\n- **WHEN** `auth_token` is not provided and `read_token_from_file` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL return empty string and `auth_token` SHALL be set to `None` (no Authorization header will be set)\n\n### Requirement: Session lifecycle with context manager support\nThe system SHALL support context manager protocol via `__enter__` and `__exit__`, create session via control plane if `session_id` not provided, and cleanup resources on exit.\n\n#### Scenario: Context manager entry with existing session_id\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(session_id=\"existing-session\")` is created\n- **WHEN** the client enters a context manager block via `with client:`\n- **THEN** `__enter__` SHALL return `self` without creating a new session\n\n#### Scenario: Context manager entry creates new session\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is created without `session_id`\n- **WHEN** the client enters a context manager block\n- **THEN** the system SHALL call `ControlPlaneClient.create_session()`, set `session_id` to returned value, initialize `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient`, and return `self`\n\n#### Scenario: Context manager normal exit\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` is used in a `with` block and `session_id` was created during entry\n- **WHEN** the block exits normally\n- **THEN** `__exit__` SHALL call `stop()`, which closes data-plane client, deletes control-plane session via `ControlPlaneClient.delete_session()`, and closes control-plane HTTP session\n\n#### Scenario: Context manager exit with exception\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` is used in a `with` block and an exception occurs in the block\n- **WHEN** the block exits with exception\n- **THEN** `__exit__` SHALL call `stop()` to clean up resources, then re-raise the exception with exception info passed to `__exit__`\n\n#### Scenario: Manual stop after context manager\n- **GIVEN** a `CodeInterpreterClient` has already exited its context manager and `stop()` was called\n- **WHEN** `stop()` is called again manually\n- **THEN** subsequent calls SHALL be idempotent and not raise errors\n\n### Requirement: Data plane initialization failure handling\nThe system SHALL handle data plane initialization failures by cleaning up created sessions before re-raising.\n\n#### Scenario: Data plane init fails after session creation\n- **GIVEN** `session_id` was not provided and `ControlPlaneClient.create_session()` succeeded returning \"new-session-123\"\n- **WHEN** `_init_data_plane()` raises an exception during initialization\n- **THEN** the client SHALL log a warning message, call `ControlPlaneClient.delete_session(\"new-session-123\")`, set `session_id` to `None`, and re-raise the original exception\n\n#### Scenario: Data plane init fails with existing session\n- **GIVEN** `session_id=\"existing-456\"` was provided to constructor\n- **WHEN** `_init_data_plane()` raises an exception\n- **THEN** the client SHALL NOT attempt to delete the session (as it was not created by this client), but SHALL re-raise the exception\n\n### Requirement: Command execution with timeout and error handling\nThe system SHALL execute shell commands via data plane, parse JSON response, handle non-zero exit codes, and support custom timeouts.\n\n#### Scenario: Successful command execution\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient` is initialized and session is active\n- **WHEN** `execute_command(\"echo 'hello world'\")` is called with default timeout\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST to `api/execute` with JSON `{\"command\": [\"echo\", \"hello world\"], \"timeout\": \"120s\"}`, wait for response, and return `stdout` from response JSON\n\n#### Scenario: Command with non-zero exit code\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command(\"ls /nonexistent\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the response JSON contains `exit_code: 1` and `stderr: \"No such file or directory\"`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL raise `CommandExecutionError(exit_code=1, stderr=\"No such file or directory\", command=\"ls /nonexistent\")`\n\n#### Scenario: Custom timeout for command execution\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command(\"sleep 10\", timeout=30.0)` is called\n- **WHEN** the request is prepared\n- **THEN** the body SHALL include `timeout: \"30s\"` and the HTTP read timeout SHALL be `32.0` seconds (30 + 2.0 buffer)\n\n#### Scenario: Command timeout without custom override\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command(\"long-running-command\")` is called without timeout parameter\n- **WHEN** the default timeout is applied\n- **THEN** the body SHALL include `timeout: \"120s\"` (from `self.timeout`) and read timeout SHALL be `122.0` seconds\n\n#### Scenario: Command with list argument format\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command([\"ls\", \"-la\", \"/tmp\"])` is called with list of strings\n- **WHEN** the command is executed\n- **THEN** the data plane SHALL receive the list directly in the JSON body `{\"command\": [\"ls\", \"-la\", \"/tmp\"], \"timeout\": \"120s\"}`\n\n### Requirement: Code execution with language-specific handling\nThe system SHALL support `run_code()` for multiple languages with special handling for Python via file write and execute.\n\n#### Scenario: Python code execution\n- **GIVEN** `run_code(language=\"python\", code=\"print('hello')\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the method executes\n- **THEN** the system SHALL generate timestamped filename (e.g., `code_20250411_123456.py`), call `write_file(content=\"print('hello')\", remote_path=\"<filename>\")`, then call `execute_command(f\"python3 {filename}\")` and return result\n\n#### Scenario: Python code with alternative language identifier\n- **GIVEN** `run_code(language=\"py\", code=\"x = 1 + 2; print(x)\")` is called\n- **WHEN** language is detected as Python variant\n- **THEN** the system SHALL use the same file-write-and-execute pattern as `\"python\"` or `\"python3\"`\n\n#### Scenario: Non-Python code execution\n- **GIVEN** `run_code(language=\"bash\", code=\"echo 'hello from bash'\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the language is not a Python variant\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST directly to data plane `run_code` endpoint with `{\"language\": \"bash\", \"code\": \"echo 'hello from bash'\"}` body\n\n### Requirement: File operations via data plane\nThe system SHALL support write, upload, download, and list file operations with proper encoding and headers.\n\n#### Scenario: Write file with base64 encoding\n- **GIVEN** `write_file(content=\"hello world\", remote_path=\"/tmp/test.txt\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the request is sent\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST to `api/files` with JSON `{\"content\": \"<base64>\", \"path\": \"/tmp/test.txt\", \"mode\": \"0644\"}` where content is base64-encoded\n\n#### Scenario: Upload file via multipart\n- **GIVEN** `upload_file(local_path=\"/local/file.txt\", remote_path=\"/remote/file.txt\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the multipart request is sent\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST to `api/files` with `files={'file': open('/local/file.txt', 'rb')}`, `data={'path': '/remote/file.txt', 'mode': '0644'}`, and header `x-agentcube-session-id: <session_id>`\n\n#### Scenario: Download file with streaming\n- **GIVEN** `download_file(remote_path=\"/data/result.json\", local_path=\"./result.json\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the file is downloaded\n- **THEN** the system SHALL GET `api/files/data/result.json` (cleaned path) with `stream=True`, write response content to `./result.json`, and close response after writing\n\n#### Scenario: List files in directory\n- **GIVEN** `list_files(path=\"/home/user\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the request completes\n- **THEN** the system SHALL GET `api/files?path=/home/user` and return the JSON response (typically file listing)\n\n#### Scenario: List files default path\n- **GIVEN** `list_files()` is called without path argument\n- **WHEN** the request is sent\n- **THEN** the system SHALL use default path `.` and query `api/files?path=.`\n\n### Requirement: HTTP session management and connection pooling\nThe system SHALL use `requests.Session` with `HTTPAdapter` for connection pooling on control plane and data plane clients.\n\n#### Scenario: Create session with default pool settings\n- **GIVEN** `create_session()` is called without arguments\n- **WHEN** the session is created\n- **THEN** the system SHALL create `requests.Session`, mount `HTTPAdapter` with `pool_connections=10` and `pool_maxsize=10` for both `http://` and `https://`, and return the session\n\n#### Scenario: Control plane client with custom pool settings\n- **GIVEN** `ControlPlaneClient(pool_connections=20, pool_maxsize=20)` is initialized\n- **WHEN** the HTTP session is created\n- **THEN** the system SHALL use the custom pool values when calling `create_session()`\n\n#### Scenario: Data plane client uses provided session\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient` is constructed with all required parameters\n- **WHEN** initialization completes\n- **THEN** the client SHALL create its own HTTP session via `create_session()` with configured pool settings\n\n#### Scenario: Closing sessions\n- **GIVEN** a client has an active `requests.Session`\n- **WHEN** `close()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL call `self.session.close()` to properly close the session and release connections\n\n### Requirement: Logger configuration\nThe system SHALL configure logging with `get_logger()` utility supporting name and level parameters.\n\n#### Scenario: Logger with default INFO level\n- **GIVEN** `get_logger(\"agentcube.code_interpreter\")` is called\n- **WHEN** the logger is created\n- **THEN** the system SHALL return a `logging.Logger` instance with name `\"agentcube.code_interpreter\"` and level `logging.INFO`\n\n#### Scenario: Logger with custom level\n- **GIVEN** `get_logger(\"agentcube.client\", level=logging.DEBUG)` is called\n- **WHEN** the logger is created\n- **THEN** the system SHALL return a logger with level set to `logging.DEBUG`\n\n#### Scenario: Client initialization sets logger\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(verbose=True)` is initialized\n- **WHEN** the logger is set\n- **THEN** the client SHALL create logger with level based on `verbose` flag (DEBUG if True, INFO if False)\n\n### Requirement: Session header injection for data plane requests\nThe system SHALL inject `x-agentcube-session-id` header into all data plane requests.\n\n#### Scenario: Request includes session header\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient(session_id=\"session-abc\")` is initialized\n- **WHEN** any `_request()` method call is made\n- **THEN** the request headers SHALL include `x-agentcube-session-id: session-abc`\n\n#### Scenario: Multipart upload includes session header\n- **GIVEN** `upload_file()` is called\n- **WHEN** the multipart POST is prepared\n- **THEN** the request SHALL explicitly set `x-agentcube-session-id` header alongside the multipart files and data\n\n#### Scenario: JSON request includes session header\n- **GIVEN** `execute_command()` is called with a JSON body\n- **WHEN** the POST request is sent\n- **THEN** the request SHALL include both `Content-Type: application/json` and `x-agentcube-session-id: <session_id>` headers\n\n### Requirement: Base URL construction for data plane\nThe system SHALL construct data plane base URL from router URL, namespace, and CR name unless explicitly provided.\n\n#### Scenario: Base URL from router and metadata\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient(router_url=\"http://router:9000\", namespace=\"default\", cr_name=\"my-interpreter\")` is initialized without `base_url`\n- **WHEN** the base URL is constructed\n- **THEN** `self.base_url` SHALL be `http://router:9000/v1/namespaces/default/code-interpreters/my-interpreter/invocations/`\n\n#### Scenario: Explicit base URL overrides construction\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient(base_url=\"http://custom:8080/custom/path/\")` is provided\n- **WHEN** initialization completes\n- **THEN** `self.base_url` SHALL be `http://custom:8080/custom/path/` without any router-based construction\n\n### Requirement: Control plane session creation and deletion\nThe system SHALL create sessions via POST to control plane API and delete via DELETE with 404 tolerance.\n\n#### Scenario: Create session returns session ID\n- **GIVEN** `ControlPlaneClient(base_url=\"http://wm:8080\")` is initialized\n- **WHEN** `create_session(name=\"test\", namespace=\"dev\", ttl=1800, metadata={\"key\": \"value\"})` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL POST `http://wm:8080/v1/code-interpreter` with JSON body containing all parameters and return the `sessionId` from response\n\n#### Scenario: Create session missing session ID in response\n- **GIVEN** the control plane POST succeeds but response JSON lacks `sessionId` field\n- **WHEN** the response is parsed\n- **THEN** the system SHALL raise `ValueError` indicating missing `sessionId`\n\n#### Scenario: Delete session success\n- **GIVEN** `delete_session(\"session-123\")` is called and server returns 200 or 204\n- **WHEN** the response is processed\n- **THEN** the method SHALL return `True`\n\n#### Scenario: Delete session 404 treated as success\n- **GIVEN** `delete_session(\"session-404\")` is called and server returns 404\n- **WHEN** the response is received\n- **THEN** the method SHALL return `True` (session already deleted)\n\n#### Scenario: Delete session other failure\n- **GIVEN** `delete_session(\"session-err\")` is called and server returns 500\n- **WHEN** the error occurs\n- **THEN** the method SHALL log the error and return `False`\n\n### Requirement: Verbose mode logging\nThe system SHALL support verbose mode for debug logging across client operations.\n\n#### Scenario: Verbose mode enabled\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(verbose=True)` is initialized\n- **WHEN** operations like command execution or file transfers occur\n- **THEN** the client SHALL log debug-level messages including request details, response status, and timing information\n\n#### Scenario: Verbose mode disabled\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(verbose=False)` is initialized (default)\n- **WHEN** operations occur\n- **THEN** the client SHALL log only INFO-level and above messages (errors, warnings, info)\n\n### Requirement: TTL parameter handling\nThe system SHALL use the TTL parameter when creating sessions for session expiration control.\n\n#### Scenario: Custom TTL for session creation\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(ttl=7200)` is initialized without `session_id`\n- **WHEN** a new session is created via control plane\n- **THEN** the request body SHALL include `ttl: 7200` to set session expiration to 2 hours\n\n#### Scenario: Default TTL when not specified\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is initialized without explicit TTL\n- **WHEN** a new session is created\n- **THEN** the request body SHALL include `ttl: 3600` (default 1 hour)\n\n### Requirement: Namespace parameter propagation\nThe system SHALL propagate namespace parameter through control plane and data plane URL construction.\n\n#### Scenario: Custom namespace in constructor\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient(namespace=\"production\")` is initialized\n- **WHEN** session is created and data plane is initialized\n- **THEN** the control plane request SHALL include `namespace: \"production\"` and data plane base URL SHALL include `/namespaces/production/`\n\n#### Scenario: Default namespace\n- **GIVEN** `CodeInterpreterClient()` is initialized without namespace\n- **WHEN** initialization completes\n- **THEN** namespace SHALL default to `\"default\"` in both control plane request and data plane URL\n\n### Requirement: Metadata support in session creation\nThe system SHALL support optional metadata dictionary when creating sessions.\n\n#### Scenario: Session with metadata\n- **GIVEN** `ControlPlaneClient.create_session(name=\"test\", namespace=\"dev\", metadata={\"owner\": \"user1\", \"purpose\": \"data-analysis\"})` is called\n- **WHEN** the request body is prepared\n- **THEN** the JSON SHALL include `metadata: {\"owner\": \"user1\", \"purpose\": \"data-analysis\"}`\n\n#### Scenario: Session without metadata\n- **GIVEN** `create_session(name=\"test\", namespace=\"dev\")` is called without metadata parameter\n- **WHEN** the request body is prepared\n- **THEN** the JSON SHALL include `metadata: null` or omit the metadata field\n\n## Acceptance Criteria Summary\n\n1. ✅ Client initialization resolves environment variables correctly\n2. ✅ Context manager protocol properly manages lifecycle\n3. ✅ Data plane failures trigger cleanup before re-raising\n4. ✅ Commands execute with proper timeout and error handling\n5. ✅ Code execution handles Python specially via file operations\n6. ✅ File operations (write, upload, download, list) work correctly\n7. ✅ HTTP sessions use connection pooling\n8. ✅ Logging configured with appropriate levels\n9. ✅ Session headers injected in all data plane requests\n10. ✅ Base URLs constructed correctly for data plane\n11. ✅ Control plane session create/delete work with 404 tolerance\n12. ✅ Verbose mode provides debug logging when enabled\n13. ✅ TTL and namespace parameters propagate correctly\n14. ✅ Optional metadata supported in session creation\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- `requests` library for HTTP client functionality\n- `PyJWT>=2.0.0` for JWT token handling (if needed)\n- `cryptography` for cryptographic operations (if needed)\n- Python >=3.10\n\n## References\n\n- Base Design: `python-sdk/design.md`\n- Base Specification: `python-sdk/spec.md`\n- AR: AR-027 — SDK CodeInterpreterClient","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md","exists":true,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775876827417,"end":1775876827519}}}}
